## Justice and Retribution: Moral and Social Considerations

Beyond deterrence, capital punishment is often defended on grounds of justice and retribution. The principle of “an eye for an eye” resonates deeply in many societies, reflecting the belief that the most heinous crimes deserve the severest penalties. Execution is seen as a just response to murder, providing closure and a sense of justice to victims’ families ([ArticleMyriad, n.d.](https://www.articlemyriad.com/argument-favor-capital-punishment/); [Columbia University, 2012](http://www1.cs.columbia.edu/~unger/articles/deathPenalty.html)).

### Victims’ Families and Societal Peace of Mind

Capital punishment can alleviate the pain and suffering of victims’ families by ensuring that convicted murderers cannot harm others again. It also addresses societal demands for justice, which may otherwise manifest as vigilante violence or social unrest ([Bartleby, n.d.](https://www.bartleby.com/essay/Capital-Punishment-Should-Be-Mandatory-FKZGWUKTGXZQ); [Columbia University, 2012](http://www1.cs.columbia.edu/~unger/articles/deathPenalty.html)).

### Ethical and Legal Safeguards

While capital punishment involves the deliberate taking of life, it is administered through a legal process with safeguards intended to minimize errors and ensure fairness. Advocates argue that the death penalty is a measured and lawful response to the gravest offenses, distinguishing it from extrajudicial killings or revenge killings ([Bartleby, n.d.](https://www.bartleby.com/essay/Capital-Punishment-Should-Be-Mandatory-FKZGWUKTGXZQ)).

---

## Practical Considerations: Costs, Crime Control, and Public Opinion

### Cost Implications

Contrary to popular belief, capital punishment cases often incur higher costs than life imprisonment due to lengthy trials, appeals, and incarceration on death row. Studies indicate that death penalty cases can cost approximately $700,000 more per case than non-capital cases, primarily due to pretrial detention and extended legal processes ([InmatesPlus, 2019](https://inmatesplus.com/the-cost-of-death-penalty-vs-life-in-prison/)). While this challenges the economic efficiency of capital punishment, proponents argue that the societal benefits of deterrence and justice justify these expenses.

### Law Enforcement and Crime Control

A majority of police chiefs surveyed do not believe capital punishment is an effective law enforcement tool, favoring alternative crime control methods ([Office of Justice Programs, 1998](https://www.ojp.gov/ncjrs/virtual-library/abstracts/does-capital-punishment-deter-crime)). However, supporters contend that the death penalty complements broader crime control strategies by specifically targeting the most dangerous offenders and preventing recidivism ([Daily Signal, 2014](https://www.dailysignal.com/2014/10/04/capital-punishment-works-it-deters-crime/)).

### Public Support

Public opinion polls in the United States and Canada generally show majority support for capital punishment, reflecting societal endorsement of its use as a deterrent and a form of justice ([NovelGuide, n.d.](https://novelguide.com/reportessay/social-issues/political-issues/benefits-capital-punishment)).

