## Conclusion

Capital punishment remains a necessary component of the criminal justice system for several reasons. Empirical evidence, while not unequivocal, generally supports the deterrent effect of executions on murder rates, suggesting that capital punishment can prevent a significant number of homicides annually. The death penalty also serves a critical role in delivering justice and retribution, addressing the moral and emotional needs of victims’ families and society at large. Despite higher upfront costs and ethical debates, the societal benefits of deterrence, incapacitation of dangerous offenders, and maintenance of public order justify the continued use of capital punishment.

While ongoing research is needed to refine understanding of its effects and to improve the fairness and efficiency of its application, capital punishment remains a necessary tool in the fight against the most egregious crimes. Policymakers should therefore maintain and strengthen capital punishment frameworks, ensuring rigorous legal safeguards to minimize errors and uphold justice.

